5.	Part B - Priority Queue Using Doubly Circular Linked List 
The sorted list from Part A is used as a priority queue. Dequeue removes the front patient, which has the highest priority. Enqueue inserts a patient into the correct sorted position according to severity and arrivalOrder. 
Step 	Operation 	Reason 	List State 
1 	dequeue() 	Sara leaves first because severity 9 and earlier arrivalOrder than Zara. 	P6 -> P4 -> P7 -> P1 -> P3 -> P5 
2 	enqueue P8 Nida(9,8) 	Inserted between Zara and Hina. 	P6 -> P8 -> P4 -> P7 -> P1 -> P3 -> P5 
3 	dequeue() 	Zara leaves because severity 9 and arrivalOrder 6 is before Nida arrivalOrder 8. 	P8 -> P4 -> P7 -> P1 -> P3 -> P5 
4 	enqueue P9 Tariq(10,9) 	Inserted at head because severity 10 is highest. 	P9 -> P8 -> P4 -> P7 -> P1 -> P3 -> P5 
5 	dequeue() 	Tariq leaves because severity 10 is highest. 	P8 -> P4 -> P7 -> P1 -> P3 -> P5 
 
The enqueuePatient() function updates both next and prev links, so the doubly circular invariant remains valid. 
6.	Part C - Stack, Reversal, and Infix to Postfix 
Patients remaining after Part B are pushed into a linked-list stack in the current queue order. The code then reverses the stack using one queue. 
Action 	Stack State 
Push 108 	TOP -> 108 
Push 104 	TOP -> 104 -> 108 
Push 107 	TOP -> 107 -> 104 -> 108 
Push 101 	TOP -> 101 -> 107 -> 104 -> 108 
Push 103 	TOP -> 103 -> 101 -> 107 -> 104 -> 108 
Push 105 	TOP -> 105 -> 103 -> 101 -> 107 -> 104 -> 108 
 
  
 
Figure 2: Stack mapping, actual IDs, and postfix result. 
Step 	Trace 
Pop phase 	105, 103, 101, 107, 104, 108 are popped from stack and enqueued. 
Push phase 	105, 103, 101, 107, 104, 108 are dequeued and pushed back. 
Final reversed stack 	TOP -> 108 -> 104 -> 107 -> 101 -> 103 -> 105 
 
Symbol 	Action 	Output 
A 	Add to output 	A 
+ 	Push operator 	A 
B 	Add to output 	AB 
) 	Pop + to output 	AB+ 
* 	Push operator 	AB+ 
C 	Add to output 	AB+C 
- 	Push operator 	AB+C 
D 	Add to output 	AB+CD 
) 	Pop - to output 	AB+CD- 
END 	Pop * 	AB+CD-* 
 
7.	Part D - Binary Search Tree 
The code builds a BST using the insertion order 104, 102, 106, 101, 103, 105, 107. This makes patientID 104 the root and gives it two children, so the two-child deletion requirement is demonstrated clearly. 
  
Figure 3: BST after all insertions. 
Inserted ID 	Reason / Position 
104 	Root node 
102 	Less than 104, goes left 
106 	Greater than 104, goes right 
101 	Less than 104 and 102, goes left of 102 
103 	Less than 104 but greater than 102, goes right of 102 
105 	Greater than 104 but less than 106, goes left of 106 
107 	Greater than 104 and 106, goes right of 106 
 
Traversal 	Sequence 
Inorder 	101 102 103 104 105 106 107 
Preorder 	104 102 101 103 106 105 107 
Postorder 	101 103 102 105 107 106 104 
 
Observation: Inorder traversal of a valid BST returns sorted values because it visits left subtree, root, and then right subtree. 
Deletion method: The code uses the inorder successor. The successor of 104 is 105, because 105 is the smallest node in the right subtree. Replacing 104 with 105 keeps the BST property valid. 
  
Figure 4: BST after deleting 104 using inorder successor. 
  
Figure 5: Balance check and rotation result. 
8.	Part E - Merge Sort on Inorder Sequence 
After deleting 104, the inorder sequence used by the code is 101, 102, 103, 105, 106, 107. Merge sort recursively splits and then merges this array. 
  
Figure 6: Complete merge sort recursion/split tree. 
Step 	Detail 
Final left half 	101 102 103 
Final right half 	105 106 107 
Comparison 1 	101 vs 105 -> place 101 
Comparison 2 	102 vs 105 -> place 102 
Comparison 3 	103 vs 105 -> place 103 
Remaining 	Copy 105, 106, 107 
Final array 	101 102 103 105 106 107 
 
Classmate argument: Correct. Inorder traversal of a BST is already sorted. Merge sort is therefore not needed for ordering here, but the algorithm still runs because the function does not check whether the array is already sorted. 
