New patient: P10, patientID 110, name Ayesha, severity 6, arrivalOrder 10. According to the sorted priority order, Ayesha is inserted between Hina(severity 7) and Hamza(severity 5). 
Pointer Update 	Meaning 
current->next = newNode 	Hina points forward to Ayesha 
newNode->prev = current 	Ayesha points backward to Hina 
newNode->next = after 	Ayesha points forward to Hamza 
after->prev = newNode 	Hamza points backward to Ayesha 
 
List after insertion: P8(108,Nida,9) <-> P4(104,Hina,7) <-> P10(110,Ayesha,6) <-> P7(107,Hamza,5) <-> P1(101,Ali,4) <-> P3(103,Usman,4) <-> P5(105,Bilal,2). 
Forward traversal: 108 104 110 107 101 103 105. 
Backward traversal: 105 103 101 107 110 104 108. 
Item 	Value 
Total severity 	9 + 7 + 6 + 5 + 4 + 4 + 2 = 37 
Patients 	7 
Average 	37 / 7 = 5.28571 
Above average 	Nida(9), Hina(7), Ayesha(6) 
Count 	3 
 
10.	Part G - Written Analysis 
10.1	Bottleneck and Better Replacement 
For a system with 1,000,000 patient records, the slowest operation depends on usage. The initial Bubble Sort is expensive because it has O(n^2) time complexity. In the running priority queue, sorted insertion also scans the linked list, so enqueue can take O(n). A better replacement for priority handling is a heap-based priority queue. A heap supports insertion and deletion of highest priority in O(log n), which is much better for a large hospital system. 
10.2	Memory Trade-off 
On a 64-bit system, one pointer takes 8 bytes. A singly linked list node has one pointer (next), while a doubly linked list node has two pointers (next and prev). Therefore, the extra memory per node is exactly 8 bytes. For 1,000,000 patients, the extra memory is 8,000,000 bytes, which is about 7.63 MB. This trade-off is justified because the lab performs backward traversal, deletion, and circular pointer verification. 
10.3	Selection Sort vs Bubble Sort 
Bubble Sort swaps from Part A = 10. Selection Sort swaps from the program = 6. Therefore, Selection Sort performs fewer swaps than Bubble Sort on this exact data. 
